  "doc_id": "54383",
  "text": "While most specific interactors showed stimulus-independent binding to APC, we also identified dynamic interaction changes upon Wnt3a activation (Figures 2 and 4) such as the enhanced binding of APC to β-catenin. Since the major mechanism of Wnt activation is stabilization of β-catenin leading to its accumulation, this could simply be the result of more available β-catenin. We likewise observed increased binding of α-catenin to APC. α-Catenin is reported to indirectly associate with APC via β-catenin, [CITATION_1] these three proteins contact each other at microtubule ends. [CITATION_2] Cytosolic complexes of α-and β-catenin have also been described. 63 Thus dynamic α-catenin binding to APC is most likely due to its association with increased levels of β-catenin. Furthermore, APC binds β-catenin not only within the destruction complex but also in the nucleus to enhance β-catenin nuclear export in the non-Wnt activated cell.",
